ProbableCause: The pilot experiencing the featureless terrain illusion during the approach which gave the perception that the airplane was at a higher altitude over the glassy water surface than it was  resulting in the airplane impacting the water.
The pilot’s inadequate preflight inspection and fuel planning  which resulted in a total loss of engine power due to fuel exhaustion.
The pilot’s failure to properly configure the airplane for landing.
The pilot’s failure to maintain clearance from trees during a go-around with a tailwind.
The pilot's excessive application of the airplane’s wheel brakes during the landing roll  which resulted in a nose over.
The pilot’s failure to maintain directional control during landing roll which resulted in a runway excursion.
The pilot’s failure to maintain directional control during takeoff in variable and gusty wind  which resulted in a ground loop.
The pilot’s failure to maintain directional control during landing roll.
The pilot’s decision to continue the landing attempt with insufficient runway remaining  which resulted in a runway overrun and collision with a fence.
The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during takeoff.
AirportName: San Luis Obispo County Regional Airport

ProbableCause: The pilot's inadvertent application of brakes during landing  which resulted in a nose over.
The pilot’s failure to maintain control of the glider during takeoff.
The pilot’s exceedance of the airplane’s critical angle of attack during climb out from an aborted landing.
AirportName: Mojave Air and Space Port/Rutan Field

ProbableCause: The airplane’s impact with the ocean for undetermined reasons based on the available evidence.
The pilot’s improper fuel planning  which resulted in fuel exhaustion and a total loss of power to both engines.
The pilot's failure to maintain obstacle clearance which resulted in an in-flight collision with a tree. Contributing to the accident was his impairment from the effects of alcohol consumption.
The pilot’s failure to attain a proper touchdown point  which resulted in a runway overrun and collision with terrain.
The pilot’s failure to maintain airplane control during takeoff with a left quartering crosswind.

The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during takeoff. Contributing to the accident was the pilot inadvertently using a runway that resulted in a tailwind condition and the flight instructors delayed remedial action.
The pilot's decision to land on an unsuitable landing surface  which resulted in a nose-over.
The pilot's delayed decision to abort the takeoff when the airplane was not attaining sufficient airspeed for takeoff and subsequently departed the end of the lake and collided with terrain.
The pilot’s failure to maintain directional control while landing and the flight instructors delayed remedial action.
The pilot’s failure to maintain directional control while landing with a crosswind.
Operator: HCH AVIATION HOLDINGS LLC - SERIES N439FJ

ProbableCause: The pilot’s failure to maintain the airplane’s directional control during the takeoff roll.
The pilot's failure to maintain a stabilized approach and his delayed action to perform a go-around  resulting in a collision with the runway surface.
The pilot’s failure to maintain directional control during a gusty crosswind landing.
The pilot’s loss of directional control during landing  which resulted in a collision with a snowbank.

The pilots’ inadequate fuel planning and failure to monitor the fuel consumption which resulted in a total loss of engine power due to fuel exhaustion and a subsequent forced landing into wooded terrain. Contributing to the accident was the flight instructor’s inadequate supervision during the instructional flight.
The truck driver’s to see and avoid the airplane  which resulted in a collision.
The flight instructor’s lack of remedial action to the student pilot’s inadequate landing flare  which resulted in a hard landing and a loss of directional control.
The pilot’s failure to see and avoid transmission wires during the landing approach.
A loss of engine oil due for undetermined reasons  which resulted in failed connecting rods and total loss of engine power.

Mechanically distressed reduction gears causing an engine overspeed and turbine blade tensile overload and subsequent uncontainment. Contributing to the uncontainment was the operator’s use of the engine after knowingly purchasing the engine in an unserviceable condition and only conducting a periodic inspection before flight.
